==English==
===Etymology===
From the [[Bible]] story of workmen hired at the eleventh hour (ie. late in the day).
: ''about the eleventh hour he went out, and found others standing idle'' &mdash; [[w:King James Bible|King James Bible]], Matthew 20:9

===Noun===
'''[[eleventh]] [[hour]]''' (often, ''at the eleventh hour'' or ''in the eleventh hour'')
#{{idiom}} nearly too [[late]]; the [[last minute]]
#:''Do not wait until the '''eleventh hour''' to begin the assignment.''

The Eleventh Hour is a figure of speech referring to the last moments before a deadline, or meant to imply that a decisive or "final" moment is near.
